node.text:
This is a male Mwanza flat-headed rock agama (Agama mwanzae), which can be found scrabbling around in Tanzania, Rwanda, and Kenya. It sometimes gets confused for the equally beautiful red-headed rock agama, whose Latin name is an easy one to remember (Agama agama).

They are sexually dimorphic so only the males are vividly colored, while the females are mottled and brown. The males are known for trying to catch the eye of potential mates by doing a sexy head-bobbing dance. 

As two tonal animals that are very good at climbing rocks, it’s perhaps unsurprising that the males have earnt the species the nickname “Spider-Man”.

node.text:
Astronomers discover cosmic “dancing ghosts”

Astronomers have observed what they have dubbed “dancing ghosts” deep in space for the first time. These cosmic dance partners are clouds of electrons shaped into being by the intergalactic winds of two supermassive black holes about a billion light-years apart. 

Discovered as part of the new sky mapping project using the huge new radio telescope, the Australian Square Kilometre Array Pathfinder, astronomers have never seen these clouds before. They’re not sure where the wind is coming from, why it’s so tangled, or what’s causing the emission. In fact, they’ve dubbed all new as-yet unexplained phenomena seen in this survey as WTFs. Expect many more WTFs on the horizon. 

Image credit: Jayanne English/EMU/Dark Energy Survey, Norris et al., arXiv, 2021

A cannabis-based mouth spray is set to be tested as a potential treatment for an aggressive form of brain tumor called glioblastoma, marking the first-ever major human trial involving medical cannabis as a cancer therapy. Known as Sativex, the spray is already approved for use as a treatment for muscle spasms in patients with multiple sclerosis, and pre-clinical investigations have indicated that it is well tolerated by glioblastoma patients.

Happy #FungiFriday! Clathrus Archeri, often known as "Octopus Stinkhorn" or "Devil's Fingers" is a fungus you wouldn't want to mess with. Over the course of a few days, its vivid red limbs sprout from small egg-like pouches before unfurling and spreading out like demonic hands clawing their way out of the abyss. Once fully developed, the arms exude gleba, a black, sticky spore-carrying material.
 
The fungus' most repulsive quality, outside its appearance, is its odor, which is believed to smell strongly of rotting flesh.

Treating obese mice with the cytokine known as TSLP led to significant abdominal fat and weight loss compared to controls, according to new research published Thursday in Science from researchers in the Perelman School of Medicine at the University of Pennsylvania. Unexpectedly, the fat loss was not associated with decreased food intake or faster metabolism. Instead, the researchers discovered that TSLP stimulated the immune system to release lipids through the skin’s oil-producing sebaceous glands.
​
​​Read the whole story by clicking on this image post via the link in our bio.

Check out this smiley chap! The eastern long-necked turtle (Chelodina longicollis) is an Australian species of snake-necked turtle whose elongated neck is usually about half the length of its carapace. All the better for sticking its nose into other people’s business, some might say.

These noodly characters are carnivorous, feeding on insects, small fish, and crustaceans, and when threatened can eject a stinky secretion from their musk glands and groin. Best stay on their good side, Australia.

Renewables produced more power than coal or nuclear power in the USA last year for the first time in history, according to a new report by the Energy Information Administration. With surges in wind, solar and hydroelectric power, the renewable industry produced 21 percent of all electricity generation in the US last year, a massive increase over the previous decade.

node.text:
Meet the Himalayan monal (Lophophorus impejanus), Nepal’s national bird known to some as the Impeyan monal or Impeyan pheasant. As a high altitude species, these birds can be found strutting across the Himalayan regions of Bhutan, China, India, Myanmar, Nepal and Pakistan moving between high up grassy slopes to lower level forests in summer and winter respectively.

These pheasants are sexually dimorphic meaning the males and females don’t look the same, and the difference is quite apparent. While the females are spattered with browns, the males look fresh off the set of Joseph and the Amazing Technicolor Dreamcoat, shimmering in combination of 12 iridescent colors. 

You so fancy, Himalayan monal.

Happy #UnderwaterWednesday! Check out this beautiful rare goth manta ray spotted on Great Barrier Reef!

This haunting black manta ray, photographed this week by marine biologist @jacintashackleton, is a relatively rare occurrence, though not in the waters off Lady Elliot Island, at the southern end of the Great Barrier Reef. Around 80 of the 1,400 individual mantas identified from Lady Elliot Island are melanistic, meaning 7.5 percent of the local population sport the gothic getup. 

Of the hundreds of cartilaginous fish in the ocean, manta rays are the only ones to exhibit melanism, a condition where an excess of melanin results in a darker, sometimes jet black, coloring. These gentle giants can reach a wingtip span of up to 5 meters, twice the size of even the tallest humans.

Photos courtesy of @jacintashackleton
